e East, including Israel, North and East Africa (Morocco, Tunisia, Libya, and Ethiopia). Chronologically, articles begin with the Roman period, through the Middle Ages and Renaissance until modern times. In this collection, the reader will find a wide range of subjects reflecting various scholarly perspectives such as history; Christian-Jewish relations; Kabbalah; commentary on the Bible and Talmud; language, grammar, and translation; literature; philosophy; gastronomy; art; culture; folklore; and education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aJewszItalyxHistoryvCongresses. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  aChristian-Jewish relations.  aEuropean Jews.  aItalian Jews.  aItalian Jews’ role in the 1st millennium.  aJewish art.  aJewish culture.  aJewish folklore.  aJewish food.  aJewish heritage.  aJewish studies.  aJews in Italy.  aKabbalah.  aSouth Italy Jewish culture.  acommentary on the Bible and Talmud.  athe Diffusion of Jewish Heritage in Europe.1 aBeltrán Munar, Miguel Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBen Zeev, Miriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBen-Arié, Dror, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBornstein-Makovetsky, Leah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg, Yaniv, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrazi, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuetta, Silvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHallamish, Moshe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarel, Yaron, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMualem, Yitzhak, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go